The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sport

 Thursday, December 09, 2004 

 Panama City: Colombian boxer Carlos Meza died on Tuesday, four days after being knocked out in the ring, according to boxing officials.

 ?Unfortunately, Meza has died,? said Miguel Prado, president of Panama?s Boxing Commission.

 Meza, 26, never regained consciousness after being knocked out in the 12th round of a bantamweight bout against Panamanian Ricardo Cordoba on Friday in the Atlantic port city of Colon.

 Dr Winston Grenald, the commission?s physician, said Meza had died as a result of a coma induced by three skull fractures and the accumulation of fluid on the brain. He said doctors ?did all they could? to save the fighter from Barranquilla.

 Bangalore: Soumyadeep Roy and Mouma Das were on Wednesday crowned men?s and women?s champions in the 25th PSCB all-India inter-unit table tennis tournament here. 

 Soumyadeep, a former national champion, overcame reigning champion, A. Sharath Kamal 11-9, 10-12, 7-11, 11-4, 14-12, 8-11, 12-10. Mouma had a fairly easy outing against national champion Poulami Ghatak, beating her 11-5, 10-12, 11-7, 11-3, 11-5.

 New York: Billie-Jean King cut her final tie with the US Fed Cup team on Tuesday when she retired as coach. Billie-Jean led the US to seven Fed Cup titles as a player and four as captain. She became coach last year as a transition while Zina Garrison took over as captain.

 ?My wonderful experiences with the US Fed Cup team have provided me the special opportunity to contribute to the continued growth of women?s sports and international team tennis,? she said in a statement.

 The United States Tennis Association confirmed on Tuesday that Garrison would remain captain and would lead the US when they host Belgium in a quarter final in April. 

 Lausanne: Bulgarian weightlifter and former Olympic champion Galabin Boevskis appeal against an eight-year-ban for doping offences has been dismissed by the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS).

 Galabin, the gold medallist in the 69kg class at the 2000 Sydney Games, was banned by the International Weightlifting Federation (IWF) after an out-of-competition doping control test in October 2003 before that years world championships in Vancouver saw him give an identical urine sample to two fellow Bulgarian lifters. 

 Copenhagen: Former Denmark midfielder Stig Tofting has been fired by his club AGF Aarhus for fighting at a Christmas party, Danish daily Ekstrabladet said on its website on Tuesday.

 The 35-year-old Tofting, who served a jail sentence last year for assault, was part of the Denmark squad that reached the second round of the 2002 World Cup in South Korea and Japan. 

 London: Briton David Coulthard is to test for the Red Bull (formerly Jaguar) Racing Formula One team in Jerez this week. A statement on Wednesday said: ?Red Bull Racing confirmed today that as part of the continued winter test programme, David Coulthard will join the team in Jerez this week driving the 2004 car, the R5.?

